{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WMRLjmV5CzLpKMdGs7Wzcq","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Workflows\n     2→\n     3→Cloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4→\n     5→## Workflow Locations\n     6→\n     7→Cloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n     8→\n     9→**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) — Run inside a Docker\n    10→container via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\n    11→standard workflows for coding tasks.\n    12→\n    13→**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) — Runs on the host machine as the daemon\n    14→process. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\n    15→dispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\n    16→point for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17→\n    18→The convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    19→file is a parse error.\n    20→\n    21→## Concepts\n    22→\n    23→| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    24→|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    25→| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    26→| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    27→| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    28→| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n    29→| done     | Built-in terminal step — successful completion                     |\n    30→| abort    | Built-in terminal step — failure with error reporting              |\n    31→\n    32→## Step Types\n    33→\n    34→Step type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    35→\n    36→**agent** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    37→to the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    38→container. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    39→\n    40→**script** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    41→any deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    42→\n    43→**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) — Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    44→until it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n    45→\n    46→A step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    47→parse error.\n    48→\n    49→## DSL Syntax\n    50→\n    51→```\n    52→workflow \"implement-feature\" {\n    53→  step code {\n    54→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    55→    container {\n    56→      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n    57→      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\"]\n    58→    }\n    59→    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n    60→  }\n    61→\n    62→  step check {\n    63→    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    64→    results = [pass, fail]\n    65→  }\n    66→\n    67→  step review {\n    68→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/review.md\")\n    69→    input = step.code.output\n    70→    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n    71→  }\n    72→\n    73→  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n    74→  code:success -> check\n    75→  code:fail -> abort\n    76→  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n    77→\n    78→  check:pass -> review\n    79→  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n    80→\n    81→  review:approved -> done\n    82→  review:changes_requested -> code\n    83→}\n    84→```\n    85→\n    86→## Key Properties\n    87→\n    88→**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n    89→field makes it a script step.\n    90→\n    91→**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n    92→report. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n    93→\n    94→**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n    95→existing ones by rewiring — without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n    96→Cloche's self-evolution feature.\n    97→\n    98→**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n    99→wired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   100→\n   101→## Wire Output Mappings\n   102→\n   103→Wires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\n   104→them as environment variables into the target step:\n   105→\n   106→```\n   107→step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   108→```\n   109→\n   110→The general form:\n   111→\n   112→```\n   113→FROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n   114→```\n   115→\n   116→Where `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\n   117→starting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n   118→\n   119→| Expression | Meaning |\n   120→|---|---|\n   121→| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   122→| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   123→| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   124→| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   125→| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   126→\n   127→If the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\n   128→structure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\n   129→value is converted to a string for env var injection.\n   130→\n   131→If two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\n   132→returns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\n   133→wires to different steps without conflict.\n   134→\n   135→## The `host {}` Block\n   136→\n   137→Host workflows support a `host {}` block at the workflow level to configure agent\n   138→defaults for agent steps running on the host machine. Keys are stored with a `host.`\n   139→prefix, analogous to the `container {}` block for container workflows.\n   140→\n   141→```\n   142→workflow \"main\" {\n   143→  host {\n   144→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   145→  }\n   146→  ...\n   147→}\n   148→```\n   149→\n   150→Supported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`. Step-level `agent_command` and\n   151→`agent_args` override the workflow-level `host {}` defaults. The agent command\n   152→resolution order for host agent steps is the same as for container agent steps:\n   153→step-level > workflow-level `host {}` > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env var > default\n   154→`claude`.\n   155→\n   156→## Host Workflow Example\n   157→\n   158→```\n   159→# .cloche/host.cloche — runs on the host machine\n   160→workflow \"main\" {\n   161→  host {\n   162→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   163→  }\n   164→\n   165→  step ready-tasks {\n   166→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh 1\"\n   167→    results = [success, fail]\n   168→  }\n   169→\n   170→  step prepare-prompt {\n   171→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   172→    results = [success, fail]\n   173→  }\n   174→\n   175→  step develop {\n   176→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   177→    results       = [success, fail]\n   178→  }\n   179→\n   180→  ready-tasks:success -> prepare-prompt [\n   181→    CLOCHE_TASK_ID    = output[0].id,\n   182→    CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE = output[0].title,\n   183→    CLOCHE_TASK_BODY  = output[0].description\n   184→  ]\n   185→  ready-tasks:fail       -> abort\n   186→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop [\n   187→    CLOCHE_TASK_ID = output.task_id\n   188→  ]\n   189→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   190→  develop:success        -> done\n   191→  develop:fail           -> done\n   192→}\n   193→```\n   194→\n   195→The `ready-tasks` step outputs JSON; wire output mappings extract fields and inject\n   196→them as environment variables into `prepare-prompt`. The `workflow_name` step\n   197→dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until it completes.\n   198→\n   199→## Execution Model\n   200→\n   201→**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   202→container. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   203→wiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   204→All steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   205→\n   206→**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. Script\n   207→steps run via `sh -c` with the working directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e.\n   208→the main branch checkout), even if the project directory is a linked worktree on a\n   209→different branch. This ensures host-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs.\n   210→Workflow steps dispatch container runs via the daemon's standard run pipeline.\n   211→Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into\n   212→each step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still points to the actual project directory.\n   213→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Dpfoc28ynQqDwHgSbSci6o","session_id":"2f8bcbbf-b8aa-4f20-9779-dee3a5fa668b","uuid":"697b3dbf-5b53-4af4-b33e-9eb821e353eb"}
