{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_015ZTKyrtMCLXGv9FgESMHhe","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a thorough understanding of the codebase. Let me plan the implementation:\n\n## Design\n\nThe task is to move task assignment from the host workflow into the daemon's orchestration loop. Here's my plan:\n\n### Changes needed:\n\n1. **`internal/host/loop.go`** - Add task assignment logic:\n   - Add `TaskAssigner` interface that the loop uses to get available tasks\n   - Add dedup map tracking task IDs with timestamps\n   - Add `DedupTimeout` to `LoopConfig`\n   - Before spawning a run, call the task assigner to get open tasks, filter out deduped ones, and pass the task ID to the runner function\n   - Update the runner function signature to accept an optional task ID\n\n2. **`internal/host/runner.go`** - Accept task ID:\n   - Add `TaskID` field or parameter to `RunWithID` or a new method\n   - Set `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var on the executor\n\n3. **`internal/host/executor.go`** - Propagate task ID env var:\n   - Add `TaskEnv` field to Executor that holds extra env vars like `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`\n   - Include these in script/workflow/agent executions\n\n4. **`internal/config/config.go`** - Add configuration support...\n\nNow I need to think through the interface design more carefully. The loop needs to list available tasks by running a command and parsing JSON output, filter out tasks within the dedup window, and pass the task ID to the runner. I'm leaning toward a clean interface where a TaskAssigner handles listing available tasks.\n\nThe runner function signature changes to accept an optional taskID parameter for backward compatibility, and I'm tracking task assignments in a dedup map keyed by task ID with timestamps. Before filling slots, if a TaskAssigner is configured, the loop calls ListTasks to get available tasks, filters out those in the dedup window, and assigns them up to the MaxConcurrent limit. Now I'm tracing how environment variables flow through the execution pipeline—from the Runner creating an Executor, through script execution where env vars get set on the command, and into workflow containers. The cleanest approach is to add a TaskID field directly to the Executor so that CLOCHE_TASK_ID gets injected into the environment for script executions.\n\nFor the Runner side, I need to figure out how to pass the task ID down—either as a parameter to a new method or by adding it to the Runner struct itself, though there's a complication since the Runner gets created inside a closure in the Enable function. Loop`. Let me look at how it's wired:\n\nI'm creating a `runFn` closure that instantiates a `Runner` with the dispatcher and store, then calls its `Run` method. To support task assignment, I need to modify this function to accept a task ID parameter and pass it through to the `Runner` struct.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the implementation steps: first, I'll add a `TaskID` field to the `Runner` and make sure it gets passed down to the `Executor`, where it'll be injected as an environment variable. Then I need to define a `Task` type and `TaskAssigner` interface in the host package so different task sources can be plugged in. Finally, I'll implement a `ScriptTaskAssigner` that executes a shell command and parses the JSON output to get the task list.\n\nFor the `Loop` itself, I need to add a `TaskAssigner` field and modify the runner function signature to accept a task ID. I'll also need a dedup map to track which tasks have been assigned recently and avoid duplicates within a timeout window. The `LoopConfig` should include the list-tasks command and dedup timeout settings, and I'll wire everything up in the gRPC server's `EnableLoop` method. the workflow still handles the actual claim step, but the daemon owns task selection and dedup logic. I'm thinking the TaskAssigner interface should live in the host package since it's specific to orchestration, and I'll add fields to OrchestrationConfig for the list-tasks command and a dedup window duration.\n\nNow I'm looking at the JSON format returned by the ready-tasks script—it's an array of task objects with id, title, and description fields. For the daemon's purposes I only really need the id, though I could extract title and description for better logging.\n\nLooking at how the current workflow uses these fields, I should include all three in the Task struct and pass them as environment variables to the executor. Let me start implementing this across the necessary files.\n\nI'm planning to create a new Task type and TaskAssigner interface, then update the loop to handle deduplication and the new runner signature. I'll also need to wire up the task listing command in the config and propagate the task ID, title, and description through the executor to the script environment.\n\nNow I'm checking the test structure in the existing executor tests to make sure I follow the same patterns.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2595,"cache_read_input_tokens":47031,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2595},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2f8bcbbf-b8aa-4f20-9779-dee3a5fa668b","uuid":"27494383-09e8-4c6d-9eda-ba1feab5771b"}
